ce:section.ce:para:
Formation of carbon dots follows several mechanisms depending on the preparation techniques. However, exact mechanism of carbon dot formation has not been disclosed so far. Various researchers proposed hypothetical or partial mechanism for the formation of the CDs [97]. It is interesting to understand the mechanism, which can facilitate controlling the carbon dot physicochemical properties. Here we discussed the mechanism of CDs formation in the sonochemical synthesis. The technique originates from the extreme transient conditions induced by ultrasound, which produces unique hot spots that can achieve temperatures above 5000 K, pressures exceeding 1000 atmospheres, and heating and cooling rates in excess of 1010 Ks−1 
                     [80,98–101]. These conditions are distinct from other conventional synthesis techniques such as photochemistry, wet chemistry, hydrothermal synthesis, or flame pyrolysis [87,102]. The extreme, transient conditions produced during acoustic cavitation allow the formation of unique materials and also permit syntheses on the benchtop in a room-temperature liquid. The sonochemical degradation and carbonization of polyethylene glycol (PEG) (precursor) is a complex chemical process and it is difficult to determine the exact chemical reactions by which it occurs [82]. Considering the degree of carbonization of CDs from the organic sources via sonication and the plenty of functional groups on the surface of CDs, the common optical and fluorescence properties on the basis of our recent studies are unraveled: photogenerated carriers are at first stored in the carbon backbone, then leak fast into any possible emission states of carbon atom (single atomic layer of graphene, sp2 carbon and functional group) and traps, in which graphitic crystallinity plays the role of temporary reservoir. In this sonochemical mechanism, increased degree of carbonization and graphitic crystallinity will lead to better photostability. The mechanism of synthesis can be explained taking the example of formation of ultrafine CDs [82], Sn@CDs, and Ga@C-dots [29,103] by ultrasonic cavitation of PEG-400 as a precursor (Fig. 3
                     ). The structural and textural properties of the produced Sn@C-dots, as a primary carbon particle and secondary coating for metals, are closely linked to the reaction parameters of the sonolytic synthesis [29]. Reaction parameters such as sonication time and polymer/metal ratio were varied to get best performance [29].

Organic and inorganic fluorophores used in bioimaging are limited due to their cytotoxicity, limited fluorescence. Conjugation with antibodies is needed for cellular uptake. Due to excellent optical properties, biocompatibility, and efficiency of cellular uptake, CDs are growing as an alternative for organic and inorganic fluorophores for bioimaging [66]. The biological application of sonochemically prepared CDs have already revealed promising bio imaging results compared to other methods [27]. This is due to excellent biocompatibility of CDs generated through sonication, whereas cytotoxicity is induced in CDs prepared by chemical methods due to use of toxic chemical and experimental conditions. CDs are widely used for intracellular imaging of various types of cells including HeLa cells, HepG2 cells, and neuronal cells such as PC12 and SH-SY5Y cells [27,32,138]. Kumar et al. synthesized sonochemically metals doped CDs (M@CDs) including Ga, Sn, Zn, Ag, and Au. The interaction of M@CDs with neuron-like cells was examined for imaging and for neuronal interactions (Fig. 5
                           ). The M@CD nanocomposites are promising due to their biocompatibility, photo-stability, and potential selective affinity, paving the way for multifunctional biomedical applications [23] (Fig. 6
                           ).
